1. Literature Survey 
The literature survey focuses on studying previous research, technologies, and 
methodologies used in the field of insurance fraud detection. Insurance fraud has 
become a major challenge for insurance companies across the world. Fraudulent 
claims cause billions of dollars in losses every year, which affects both companies and 
honest policyholders. Because of this, researchers and organizations have been 
continuously working on developing intelligent systems to detect and prevent 
fraudulent activities. 
In traditional insurance systems, fraud detection was mostly done manually by human 
investigators. Investigators had to analyze claim details, customer history, and various 
supporting documents to identify suspicious activities. However, this manual process is 
slow, expensive, and inefficient when dealing with large volumes of data. As the number 
of insurance claims increases, it becomes more difficult for companies to detect fraud 
using traditional methods. 
To solve this problem, researchers introduced data mining and machine learning 
techniques to automate the fraud detection process. Machine learning algorithms can 
analyze large datasets and identify patterns that may indicate fraudulent behavior. 
These systems are capable of learning from historical data and making predictions 
about new insurance claims. 
Several machine learning algorithms have been studied and applied in fraud detection 
systems. Some of the commonly used algorithms include: 
1. Logistic Regression 
Logistic Regression is widely used for classification problems. In insurance fraud 
detection, it is used to classify claims as fraudulent or legitimate based on different 
features such as claim amount, customer information, and accident details. 
2. Decision Tree 
Decision Tree algorithms create a tree-like structure to make decisions based on 
different conditions. This method is easy to interpret and helps identify the important 
factors that contribute to fraudulent claims. 
3. Random Forest 
Random Forest is an ensemble learning method that combines multiple decision trees 
to improve prediction accuracy. It is highly effective in handling large datasets and 
reducing overfitting problems. 
4. Support Vector Machine (SVM) 
SVM is another classification algorithm used in fraud detection. It works by finding the 
optimal boundary that separates fraudulent claims from legitimate claims. 
5. Neural Networks 
Artificial Neural Networks are inspired by the human brain and are capable of identifying 
complex patterns in data. These models are often used in advanced fraud detection 
systems. 
In addition to machine learning algorithms, several data preprocessing techniques are 
also used to improve model performance. These techniques include data cleaning, 
feature selection, normalization, and handling missing values. Proper data 
preprocessing ensures that the model can learn effectively from the dataset. 
Recent studies also focus on real-time fraud detection systems that can analyze 
claims immediately after submission. These systems use advanced analytics and 
machine learning models to identify suspicious claims instantly and alert investigators. 
The proposed project builds a machine learning-based system that analyzes insurance 
claim data and predicts whether a claim is fraudulent or legitimate. By using intelligent 
algorithms and historical data, the system aims to improve the efficiency and accuracy 
of fraud detection.
